{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479911"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:34:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:34:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20905"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20905"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.11,0.08,0.4,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13780"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101951"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13780"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20905"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84409"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"659"},{"type":"tags","id":"1444"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"8307"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44973"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101951"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-day history of right ear discharge. This was preceded by several days of nasal congestion, rhinorrhoea, mild fever, and significant right ear pain. The pain improved last night, after which he noticed the ear discharge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is currently afebrile and appears well. There is purulent discharge in the right ear canal. The left tympanic membrane appears erythematous but mobile, with no effusion. His Weber test lateralises to the right ear. Rinne test is abnormal on the right and normal on the left. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment in addition to simple analgesia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ear toileting, oral amoxicillin and further review","Amoxicillin and clavulanic acid, and further review","Ear toilet alone, with further review","Ear toilet, ciprofloxacin ear drops, and further review","Trimethoprim and sulfamethoxazole, and further review"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe child described in this case presents with an acute otitis media infection that has not persisted for more than 48 hours, but with a possible suppurative complication (significant ear discharge). When there is a spontaneous resolution of otalgia followed by release of purulent fluid, a tympanic membrane perforation must be suspected. Therefore, the child should be treated as a case of acute otitis media with perforation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E Otitis media involves infection of the middle ear by pathogens ranging from viruses to various bacteria, most commonly \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EMoraxella catarrhalis\u003C/em\u003E. It most commonly presents in younger children with fever and ear pain, and can follow an upper respiratory tract infection. The build up of purulent fluid can lead to conductive hearing loss of the affected ear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first-line antibiotic of choice for this clinical presentation is \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E, in tandem with \u003Cstrong\u003Eear toileting. \u003C/strong\u003EDespite being mostly a bacterial infection, the use of antibiotics in the management of otitis media is reserved for specific high-risk groups; Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children are at higher risk of complications and chronic suppurative otitis media, so prompt oral antibiotic therapy is recommended. Therapeutic Guidelines suggest a dose of 15 mg/kg up to 500 mg orally, 8-hourly for 5 days; Otitis Media Guidelines from the Menzies School of Health Research advise a more aggressive regimen, with 50-90 mg/kg/day for at least 14 days. The patient should be also be \u003Cstrong\u003Ereviewed\u003C/strong\u003E after a week to ensure response to treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin and clavulanic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for children who have not responded adequately to amoxicillin by 48 to 72 hours. In these patients, infection may be caused by a beta-lactamase\u2013producing strain of \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003EMoraxella catarrhalis\u003C/em\u003E. It is not first-line in uncomplicated acute otitis media with perforation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEar toilet and further review\u003C/strong\u003E alone may be appropriate for non-Indigenous children with uncomplicated otitis media without perforation, but in the presence of tympanic membrane perforation and discharge, oral antibiotics are indicated. This is especially true for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children, or other high-risk groups (e.g. children aged under six months, immunocompromised, or one hearing ear). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEar toilet, ciprofloxacin ear drops, and further review\u003C/strong\u003E is not first-line for acute otitis media with new perforation. Ciprofloxacin may be added to the management of acute otitis media with perforation if discharge or bulging eardrum persists after amoxicillin treatment, and is an appropriate choice for chronic suppurative otitis media; however, topical antibiotics would not be recommended as initial management in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim and sulfamethoxazole\u003C/strong\u003E with further review would be a reasonable choice for children who have had a severe hypersensitivity reaction to a penicillin. The drug is also second-line for the management of chronic suppurative otitis media, but would not be first-line for standard therapy of acute otitis media with perforation in a child without penicillin allergy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute otitis media with tympanic membrane perforation and discharge in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children requires oral antibiotics due to higher risk of complications.","Amoxicillin is first-line for acute otitis media with perforation; amoxicillin with clavulanic acid is reserved for cases not responding to initial therapy.","Topical antibiotics are not first-line for acute otitis media with new perforation but may be considered if discharge persists after oral therapy."],"references":["Leach AJ, Morris P, Coates HLC, et al. Otitis media guidelines for Australian Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander children: summary of recommendations. Med J Aust 2021; [in press]. Available from: https://otitismediaguidelines.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/OtitisMedia_Guideline_2020.pdf","Otitis Media. Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. 2025. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Saux N, Robinson J. Management of acute otitis media in children six months of age and older. Paediatric Child Health [Internet]. 2016 [cited 2020Apr30]; Available from:\u00a0https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4758427/","Thomas JP, Berner R, Zahnert T, Dazert S. Acute Otitis Media\u2014a Structured Approach. Deutsches Arzteblatt International [Internet]. 2014Feb28 [cited 2020Apr30]; Available from:\u00a0https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3965963/","Venekamp R, Damoiseaux R, Schilder A. Acute otitis media in children. BMJ Clinical Evidence [Internet]. 2014Sep16 [cited 2020Apr30]; Available from:\u00a0https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4166866/","Morden NE, Berke EM. Topical Fluoroquinolones for Eye and Ear [Internet]. American Family Physician. 2000 [cited 2021Jun2]. Available from: https://www.aafp.org/afp/2000/1015/p1870.html","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. [cited 2021Jun2]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Acute_otitis_media/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84409"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20905"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84409"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-05T17:32:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-31T11:36:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13780"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101951"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhin